      {
        "step": 4,
        "type": "text",
        "text": "✅ **Circuit built successfully!**\n\n## Wiring Table\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| D2 | R_a (220Ω) → Seg a | Segment a driver |\n| D3 | R_b (220Ω) → Seg b | Segment b driver |\n| D4 | R_c (220Ω) → Seg c | Segment c driver |\n| D5 | R_d (220Ω) → Seg d | Segment d driver |\n| D6 | R_e (220Ω) → Seg e | Segment e driver |\n| D7 | R_f (220Ω) → Seg f | Segment f driver |\n| D8 | R_g (220Ω) → Seg g | Segment g driver |\n| D9 | Button (pin A) | Increment button |\n| GND | Button (pin B) | Button return |\n| GND | 7-seg common (gnd) | Display common cathode |\n\n## How It Works\n- **Button press** (D9): Increments the counter and updates the display.\n- **Auto-reset**: Counter wraps from 9 back to 0.\n- **Display format**: Lights appropriate segments (a–g) to show digits 0–9.\n- **Pull-up**: Button uses Arduino's internal pull-up (`INPUT_PULLUP`); pin reads LOW when pressed.\n- **Debounce**: 10ms loop delay prevents false triggers from switch bounce.\n\nEach segment has a 220Ω current-limiting resistor to keep per-pin current safe (~15mA). Total board draw is well within Uno limits."
      }
